us"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A virus\u003C/strong\u003E is unique among hepatitis viruses as it only causes acute infection and always resolves completely without progression to chronic disease. Recovery provides lifelong immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other viruses can all potentially establish chronic infection:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus\u003C/strong\u003E becomes chronic in 5-10% of adults and up to 90% of perinatal infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C virus\u003C/strong\u003E establishes chronic infection in up to 80% of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis D virus\u003C/strong\u003E requires hepatitis B virus co-infection and can cause chronic hepatitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis E virus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes acute infection but can become chronic in immunocompromised patients\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic viral hepatitis can lead to cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis A virus causes acute self-limiting infection that always resolves without chronic sequelae","Hepatitis B and C viruses commonly establish chronic infection, while hepatitis D requires hepatitis B co-infection","Hepatitis E virus typically causes acute infection but can become chronic in immunocompromised hosts"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of 